    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Towers, and a Memorial</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Louis Epstein letter on Nov 2 article says he does not oppose building memorial to World Trade Center victims, but sees new towers as better way to revitalize economy</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Longing for a Sept. 10 Skyline; Some Vocal Groups Call for Restoring the Twin Towers'' (news article, Nov. 2):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Longing for a Sept. 10 Skyline; Some Vocal Groups Call for Restoring the Twin Towers'' (news article, Nov. 2):</p>
        <p>You quoted me as the founder of the World Trade Center Restoration Movement. I do not wish to leave an impression that I am indifferent to the issue of honoring those murdered on Sept. 11.</p>
        <p>I suggested in the article that a memorial would do far less than new towers to revitalize the economy. Historically, memorials tend to become backwaters, as the events they commemorate recede from memory. But this does not mean that I am against building one.</p>
        <p>Building towers of such a scale that people will come from all over the world to marvel at them will itself be a tribute to the dead, and will ensure that a memorial alongside them will not suffer the fate of so many that have become obscure.</p>
        <p>LOUIS EPSTEIN  Carmel, N.Y., Nov. 2, 2002</p>
      </block>
